<DOCNO> AP891219-0011 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
facts and figures on romania 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
geography romania covers 91700 square miles and shares 
borders with hungary yugoslavia the soviet union and bulgaria 
the danube river empties into the black sea on romanias eastern 
coast the north of the country is dominated by the carpathian 
mountains and the center by the transylvanian alps 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the people romanias population of 23 million includes about 
17 million ethnic hungarians the largest minority and 220000 
ethnic germans romanian is the main language but hungarian 
serbian german and turkish are also spoken eighty percent of the 
population is romanian orthodox and 10 percent are catholics there 
also are 21000 jews 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
economy romania whose industry accounts for around 60 percent 
of the gross national product exports machinery metals lumber 
refined fuels and textiles agricultural products include corn 
wheat potatoes and beets natural resources include oil natural 
gas and coal 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
history romania gained independence in 1877 after some five 
centuries of ottoman rule a monarchy before world war ii the 
country was reorganized along fascist lines from 1940 until august 
23 1944 when romania switched to the allied side with the 
support of soviet troops a communistdominated government bloc won 
elections in 1946 and in 1955 romania joined the warsaw pact 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
leadership the present leader nicolae ceausescu came to 
power in 1965 noted for his moderately independent foreign policy 
in the 1960s and 1970s he is under increasing fire for his home 
policy including suppression of dissent and alleged discrimination 
against the hungarian minority efforts to repay the foreign debt 
quickly have led to growing domestic food and energy shortages in 
recent years ceausescus ringing rejection of reform is leaving 
him with fewer friends as warsaw pact allies move toward democracy 
and western countries step up criticism of romanias human rights 
records 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

