<TEXT>
a texas nuclear weapons assembly plant where 
radioactive gas was accidentally released last spring was 
unprepared for such an emergency an energy department advisory 
committee says 
it is still unclear that effective control of the situation by 
an adequately prepared response team ever took place john f 
ahearne chairman of the advisory committee on nuclear facility 
safety said in a letter about the pantex plant in amarillo texas 
the letter to energy secretary james d watkins released 
monday also raised questions about safety and environmental 
practices at pantex the nations only final assembly plant for 
nuclear bombs and missile warheads 
the committee said the response to the may release of tritium a 
radioactive gas was of variable quality 
radiation specialists and technicians responded properly to 
minimize workers exposure at the plant the report said 
missing was recognition that this unlikely event could take 
place and thus adequate procedures instrumentation and training 
were lacking the letter said 
although a quick and effective evacuation was conducted 
thereafter events are marked by confusion misread instruments 
and uncertain actions there appeared to be no plan to handle what 
surely must be an anticipated accident the report said 
pantex spokesman tom walton said the plant has begun correcting 
problems or will be addressing those in the very near future 
some safety violations were corrected on the spot 
the report said cleaning up the facility after the accident was 
estimated to cost 1 million and the psychological trauma on the 
individuals exposed 
exposure to workers however was below federal guidelines 
limiting radiation exposure and offsite exposure was trivial 
the letter said the committee found a lack of belief that 
pantex can have radiological accidents in spite of the recent 
tritium accident 
a tiger team of government and outside experts also recently 
inspected the plant and found pantex would be unable to respond 
effectively to emergencies involving releases of radioactive 
material 
watkins said those findings indicate workers lack adequate 
protection from emergency and routine exposure to radioactive 
releases and that the situation must be corrected immediately 
the advisory committee which spent two days in amarillo last 
month found an apparent lack of sophistication and depth 
regarding environmental problems at pantex 
monitoring of possible ground water contamination with wells at 
pantex also has been less than systematic the letter said 
this issue has just not received a great deal of attention 
this is particularly unfortunate since ground water contamination 
if found would be a threat to the sole source of drinking water 
for the area the letter said 
