a 1976 regulation barring people from passing 
out leaflets near the white house has been declared 
unconstitutional by a federal judge who says such a ban violates 
the first amendment and has no conceivable governmental 
interest 
us district court judge john pratt ruled monday in the case of 
carol ann fennelly charged with illegally distributing pamphlets 
in june on a street between the white house and treasury department 
the material urged passersby to write members of congress in 
favor of housing for the homeless 
regulations approved in 1970 were part of an effort to protect 
white house security by restrictions on demonstrations the 
provision at issue in fennellys case was added in 1976 to preserve 
an atmosphere of calm and tranquility at memorials and buildings 
associated with past presidents 
pratt noted that fennelly would violate the regulation by 
passing out a leaflet but could convey the same identical 
message by word of mouth without fear of arrest 
</TEXT>
