<TEXT>
prime minister mudar badran told the new 
parliament today his government will lift martial law which for 22 
years has banned large public meetings and allowed authorities to 
restrict freedom of speech 
badran seeking a vote of confidence from the newly elected 
legislature added that until martial law is formally revoked most 
of its provisions will be frozen effective immediately 
he also vowed his administration will crack down on corruption 
by public officials and criticized former governments for deficit 
spending that swelled jordans 83 billion foreign debt 
under martial law which king hussein imposed after the 1967 
arabisraeli war authorities also can close newspapers at any 
time effectively inhibiting free criticism of officials it also 
provides for special courts 
most candidates in last months general elections called for the 
lifting of martial law and many demanded the legalization of 
political parties which currently are banned 
badran said a constitutional court will be formed to secure 
citizens rights as stipulated by the constitution 
he lifted legal immunity from government officials and said he 
would put forward legislation requiring an officeholder to present 
a comprehensive and documented report of all his possessions 
the announcement of such a financial disclosure requirement was 
aimed at ensuring the integrity of public officials 
the government of prime minister zeid rifai which resigned 
earlier this year after bloody rioting was widely accused of 
corruption 
the largest bloc in the new lower house is made up of islamic 
fundamentalists or their sympathizers 
i announce in this parliament that martial law is now 
considered frozen until such laws are constitutionally 
abolished in the near future badran told the lower house of 
parliament 
it was the latest in a series of moves towards democracy and 
liberalization announced by the king and by badrans government 
which was formed dec 6 
the lower house has to approve all laws and has the power to 
throw out prime ministers and their cabinets still king hussein 
can block any laws in the royally appointed senate or through a 
veto and he has frequently used the power to dissolve parliament 
and rule by decree 
last month hussein promised a gradual reduction in the 
activities of the martial law courts and said their 
responsibilities would be transfered to civil courts 
on dec 10 badran announced his government would return 
confiscated passports and promised further amnesties for political 
