<TEXT>
china on tuesday criticized demands for greater 
democracy in hong kong as an attempt to bring the chinese 
government to its knees and limit its sovereignty after britain 
returns the colony in 1997 
it also said it was up to britain to come back to the correct 
road of friendly cooperation chinas relations with britain as 
with most western countries have deteriorated following the 
chinese army attack on prodemocracy protesters in june 
the comments came in a lengthy essay excerpted in the official 
peoples daily and other newspapers to be published in full in the 
weekly beijing review magazine the essay marked the fifth 
anniversary of the signing of the sinobritish joint declaration in 
which britain agreed to return hong kong and china agreed to let it 
remain capitalist for at least 50 years 
the essay said that although hong kong will retain a high 
degree of autonomy after 1997 its relationship to beijing will 
be that of a local government to a sovereign central state 
some people in an attempt to pit democracy against 
communism suggest that the democratic process be accelerated in 
developing hong kongs democratic system the essay said 
they stress that this is the desire of the hong kong people in 
an attempt to create a de facto situation to bring the chinese 
government to its knees these people are actually seeking under 
the pretext of democracy to establish a power pattern in hong kong 
after 1997 that will harm chinas sovereignty it said 
this we resolutely oppose 
some hong kong residents fearful of chinese rule have pressed 
the colonial government to introduce more democratic rule in the 
hope that china would find it hard to undo such reforms after 1997 
the hong kong government has agreed to allow elections in 1991 to 
fill 10 of the 56 seats in the colonys legislative council which 
is appointed by the government and local interest groups 
there also have been calls for at least 40 percent of hong 
kongs post1997 legislature to be popularly elected but the hong 
kongchinese committee drafting the colonys post1997 basic law 
recently agreed that only 30 percent of the delegates should be 
chosen by elections 
china has reiterated that it will not allow hong kong to become 
a base for antigovernment and anticommunist activity and has 
moved to include in the basic law provisions against subversive 
activity 
the essay said hong kong residents will be allowed after 1997 to 
raise opinions about chinas state affairs but only through legal 
channels 
if unsuitable means are adopted to express ones own 
viewpoints things might go contrary to their wishes and damage 
might be brought upon the friendly relationship between the 
mainland and hong kong it warned all political activity will 
have to respect the mainlands socialist system it said 
the mainlands constitution allows no political activity 
independent of the communist party 
a committee of 33 mainland delegates and 23 hong kong delegates 
is working on the final draft of hong kongs post1997 basic law 
it is to be submitted to chinas legislature in the spring for 
approval 
