<TEXT>
nazi hunters are searching for hundreds of 
newly identified lithuanian war crimes suspects believed hiding in 
the united states canada australia and britain the simon 
wiesenthal center said tuesday 
the names are listed in files of testimony from jewish survivors 
in soviet lithuania given three months ago to the yad vashem 
archives in jerusalem which is in charge of documenting the 
slayings of 6 million jews during world war ii by nazi germany 
the records were kept secret for more than four decades by an 
elderly lithuanian survivor leibl kuniuchovsky who now lives in 
sunrise fla said efraim zuroff director of the israeli office 
of the los angelesbased center known for tracking down nazi 
suspects 
this material has enormous significance based on our past 
experience this can lead us to numerous nazi war criminals now 
living in the united states canada australia and the united 
kingdom zuroff said 
he said the approximately 1300 names on the list are 
lithuanians who collaborated with the nazis during 194142 when 
most mass slayings of jews took place in the baltic republic more 
than 200000 jews are believed to have been murdered by the nazis 
in lithuania 
lithuania was a center of jewish culture in eastern europe in 
the 18th and 19th centuries and a nesting ground for the zionist 
ideology that led to the creation of israel the jewish community 
there numbered 15 million at the turn of the century and only 
26000 after world war ii 
kuniuchovsky a survivor of the jewish ghetto in the city of 
kovno took the testimony from refugees after the war on behalf of 
historical commissions set up by the allies in displaced persons 
camps in west germany zuroff said 
his records are valuable because they provide rare accounts from 
the few jews who survived the mass slayings that took place in 
isolated towns and villages zuroff said in an interview 
he said the 1300 names were gathered from 1683 pages of 
testimony that kuniuchovsky took from survivors in 171 towns and 
villages 
hundreds of the suspects were known to be alive zuroff added 
he declined to give names of the suspects suggesting this could 
harm efforts to seek them out for prosecution 
the majority were previously unknown to us he said noting 
the earlier testimony was sketchy about slayings in many isolated 
areas because survivors were few and investigators were unable to 
find them in later years 
zuroff said the wiesenthal center is tracking the suspects 
through its four branches in the united states one in toronto and 
other agencies the center is named for founder simon wiesenthal 
80 an austrianborn concentration camp survivor who has devoted 
much of his life to hunting down nazi war criminals and documenting 
the holocaust 
in addition to new suspects names kuniuchovskys file also 
contains surprising information about the numbers of lithuanians 
involved in the killings zuroff said 
it is shocking to see such a big role was played by the 
intelligentsia zuroff added were talking about school 
teachers educated people who belonged to vigilante groups or 
helped local police carry out killings 
zuroff also said he hoped legislation adopted in the past two 
years in canada and australia allowing prosecution of crimes 
committed overseas would make it easier to hunt and prosecute the 
lithuanian suspects 
