<TEXT>
the soviet union will be able to buy an 
additional 2 million metric tons of us wheat at subsidized 
prices the agriculture department said tuesday 
undersecretary richard t crowder said the wheat will be made 
available under the departments export enhancement program or 
eep the new amount is in addition to 14200 tons moscow had 
remaining under a previous allocation announced last may 2 
the soviet union is committed to buy minimum quantities of wheat 
and corn under a longterm grain agreement which began its seventh 
year on oct 1 and will expire dec 31 1990 moscow has bought 
about 800000 tons of wheat for delivery in 198990 according to 
usda records 
nearly 11 million tons of corn have been sold for 198990 
delivery along with soybeans and soybean meal 
in 198889 the sixth period under the agreement the soviet 
union bought about 54 million tons of wheat and more than 163 
million tons of corn plus soybeans soybean meal and grain 
sorghums 
a metric ton is about 2205 pounds and is equal to 367 bushels 
of wheat 
the eep arrangement allows private exporters to sell wheat and 
other designated commodities to specified countries at reduced 
prices in order to meet foreign competition the exporters then 
collect free government surpluses of grain or other products as 
bonuses or subsidies 
since eep began in 1985 more than 26 billion in subsidies has 
been paid to exporters to ship a variety of commodities to overseas 
customers as of nov 30 sales totaled 872 million tons of grain 
including 644 million tons of wheat 
the soviet union as the largest eep beneficiary has bought 
more than 175 million tons of wheat china is second at 132 
