<TEXT>
the nations dominant longdistance telephone 
company the american telephone amp telegraph co announced tuesday 
that it will cut basic daytime interstate rates an average of 13 
percent jan 1 evening rates will drop an average of 20 percent 
atampt spokesman herb linnen said the reductions were necessary 
under changes earlier this year in the federal communications 
commissions regulation of longdistance charges 
the fcc now imposes caps on atampts longdistance rates based on 
the companys longdistance expenses as opposed to a preset rate 
of return 
atampt said the lowered rates reflect reduced expenses mainly 
from reduced fees that atampt will pay in 1990 to local telephone 
companies for access to local exchanges 
john hauser a spokesman for atampts principal competitor mci 
communications corp said mci would also pass on savings in local 
telephone company access charges we will remain competitive with 
them he said 
hausers counterpart at us sprint robin pence said we are 
reviewing the filing and we intend to remain competitive 
atampt says it has about 70 percent of the longdistance market 
as measured by interstate and intrastate revenues mci is no 2 
with more than 10 percent us sprint claims 7 to 8 percent 
in filing notice with the fcc of its intent to lower rates atampt 
estimated that the reductions would save customers 300 million a 
year on interstate and international longdistance services used 
primarily by residential and small business customers 
a 10minute atampt call during daytime hours on a weekday to 
anywhere in the united states will cost 250 or less an average 
decrease of 13 percent 
linnen said a 10minute daytime call from washington to new 
york which now costs 230 would decline to 220 a drop of 43 
percent an evening call from washington to san francisco los 
angeles or dallas which now costs 167 for 10 minutes would drop 
53 percent to 158 many of the reductions would be less for 
other calls 
the mondayfriday day calling period is 8 am to 5 pm 
local time the evening period is 5 pm to 11 pm sunday 
through friday 
the night calling period for which rates will not change 
is from 11 pm to 8 am sunday through friday weekend 
calling rates identical to the night rates and also unaffected 
are in effect all day saturday and until 5 pm sunday 
international calls from the 48 contiguous states to 25 of the 
most frequently called countries will be slashed by 104 million 
the reductions will vary from country to country the countries 
will include canada mexico japan the united kingdom france 
italy israel brazil australia the philippines taiwan and korea 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

