interest of stability 
the presidency in czechoslovakia is a largely ceremonial post 
but it has great symbolic importance because of the respect the 
countrys first president tomas masaryk enjoyed in the 
independent czechoslovakia he founded in 1918 
calfa said the new president should serve only until june or 
july when czechoslovakia is to hold its first free elections in 43 
years 
havel whose works were banned when the uprising against rigid 
communist rule began a month ago has said he would serve as 
president only on an interim basis until a replacement was chosen 
by a democratically elected parliament 
havel was in prison as recently as may when he completed a 
fourmonth sentence on protestrelated charges 
jockeying over the presidency has dominated politics for nearly 
two weeks after a series of stunning opposition triumphs forced 
the communists to relinquish their monopoly on power and name the 
first government since 1948 not dominated by the party 
calfas endorsement of havel was an unprecedented show of 
support his government has been reported trying to overcome 
resistance among communist deputies to havels candidacy 
czechoslovakia has not had a president since dec 10 when 
gustav husak a member of the old guard resigned after swearing in 
the new government 
husaks resignation followed a series of leadership changes that 
removed hardline leaders associated with the crackdown after the 
warsaw pact invasion that ended the prague spring reforms of 
1968 led by alexander dubcek 
dubcek later dismissed as party chief and assigned to an 
obscure forestry job in bratislava also has been mentioned as a 
potential presidential candidate 
the communist party has been in disarray since a brutal police 
crackdown on student protesters nov 17 started the anticommunist 
revolution 
a twoday special party congress opens wednesday in prague and 
is expected to recommend more personnel and policy changes 
