savannah officials and the fbi confirmed that the parcel bomb 
that killed alderman robert robinson on monday was similar to those 
that killed 11th us circuit court of appeals judge robert s 
vance on saturday and forced the evacuation monday of the 
courthouse in atlanta that includes the 11th circuit 
an fbi agent said the alabama and georga bombs all had different 
postmarks phony return addresses and too many postage stamps 
elsewhere tuesday an anonymous caller threatened to kill a 
federal judge in alabama a package delivered to a birmingham 
ala city councilman who was a friend of vance was found to be 
harmless 
the national association for the advancement of colored people 
instructed its 1800 branch offices and seven regional offices to 
tighten security because the bombs might be racially motivated 
executive director benjamin hooks said from the organizations 
headquarters in baltimore 
the discovery of the parcel bomb at the naacps jacksonville 
office prompted police to evacuate and cordon off the building 
the bomb was disarmed inside the building with a device that 
disconnected the battery from the explosive officials said 
it was designed to kill the individual that opened this 
package or anyone else standing in the area said jacksonville 
sheriff jim mcmillan 
it had a great similarity in the packaging to the other 
bombs said willi ellison of the us bureau of alcohol tobacco 
and firearms it was addressed to no one specifically but to the 
legal staff of the naacp 
the bomb was to be taken to an fbi laboratory in washington and 
compared with the other devices ellison said 
the package arrived at the naacp office monday but had been 
left unopened a series of bomb threats and scares hit federal 
buildings around florida but no other explosive devices were found 
thornburgh said in a statement that he had contacted civil 
rights leaders to assure them that we are fully committed to the 
vigorous investigations of these crimes and the apprehension of the 
person or persons who committed them 
the fbi and thornburgh warned civil rights leaders judges and 
attorneys that the bombings may be racist attacks but the attorney 
general stressed there was no firm conclusion on motivation 
a pattern of racist attacks has to be one of the factors in 
the back of all our minds sessions told a justice department 
news conference he said the incidents have involved federal 
judges who have heard cases involving racial matters the naacp 
and a black civil rights activist 
sessions said it was quite possible more than one person was 
involved and that the bombs might be the work of an organized 
group he noted that the incidents had occurred in three states in 
the 11th circuit 
sessions said no one had claimed responsibility for the bombs 
robinson a civil rights activist and lawyer was fatally 
wounded by a mail bomb in his law office monday hours after the 
courthouse evacuation in atlanta 
although he was black a law colleague said there was little 
reason to figure him as a target of extremist bombers 
funeral services for vance will be held wednesday us supreme 
court justice anthony m kennedy who oversees the 11th circuit is 
expected to attend along with sessions and the attorney general 
fbi agent tom moore in birmingham said there were strong 
similarities between the three bombs 
fbi agent allen whitaker in birmingham said the georgia and 
alabama bombs came in similar packages but were mailed from 
different places 
there was not a common postmark whitaker said all had 
return addresses of different legitimate persons who had no 
connection with the packages 
he said the packages bore an excessive number of postage stamps 
apparently to protect the senders from a facetoface meeting 
with postal employees 
authorities in alabama said the bomb that killed vance sprayed 
nails and the atlanta constitution reported tuesday that the 
atlanta bomb also contained nails 
we believed nails were part of this bomb also and that has 
been confirmed said savannah mayor john rousakis he said he 
