<DOCNO> AP891219-0190 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a trade group representing savings and loan 
holding companies is complaining about new rules that prohibit sampls 
from releasing mailing lists of their customers names without 
permission from their customers 
the rules imposed by the office of thrift supervision provide 
that a name and address may be given out only if the customer is 
first notified and does not object within 15 days after two years 
the customer must be asked to renew the permission 
the prohibition took effect friday 
the association of thrift holding companies in a suit filed in 
us district court seeking to overturn the regulations complained 
that the rules make it difficult for thrift parent companies such 
as insurance companies and banks to crossmarket their products to 
the thrifts customers 
banks do not operate under similar restrictions and imposing the 
limits on sampls likely will hurt the governments efforts to dispose 
of failed thrifts the trade group said financial institutions 
earn money by selling their mailing lists to others 
however thrift office director m danny wall said in a 
statement the regulation strikes a reasonable balance between 
customers expectations of privacy and legitimate business 
interests of thrift institutions 
he acknowledged that in most states the rules will now be 
