<TEXT>
a light sentence of three years probation for 
admitted stock manipulator salim b sandy lewis is another sign 
that on wall street it pays to settle 
lewis pleaded guilty to three counts of securities violations 
rather than face trial and was sentenced monday to work in a new 
york drug rehabilitation clinic and pay a 250000 fine rather than 
go to prison 
some securities law experts said the term appeared fair for 
lewis crime jacking up the price of firemans fund corp stock 
in may 1986 but raised the question of whether whitecollar 
felons were being treated too leniently 
in her sentencing speech us district judge mary johnson lowe 
told lewis that your skills should not be wasted in warehousing 
you she also said his admission of guilt was a mitigating factor 
where you run into problems is the kid who sells a little 
marijuana or cocaine and gets three years said alan bromberg a 
securities law professor at southern methodist university im 
not sure hes doing any more social harm its just that hes not 
capable of doing as much social good 
lewis was ordered to work 40 hours a week for one year at daytop 
village a manhattanbased drug rehabilitation clinic he must work 
20 hours a week at the clinic in the second and third years of his 
probation lewis will work at daytop as an executive consultant 
the idea to work there was his 
boyd l jefferies the former los angeles stockbroker who 
identified lewis as part of a plea deal in which he cooperated with 
the government in july was sentenced to five years probation and 
community service and fined 250000 
two other figures in the wall street scandals still await 
sentencing after pleading guilty to securities crimes former 
takeover strategist martin siegel and former stock arbitrager 
robert freeman 
observers said the lewis case could bear on sentencing gaf corp 
vice chairman james t sherwin who was convicted last week of 
stock manipulation in a case also before lowe sherwin has done 
extensive work for a refugee relocation agency as lewis had worked 
with drugaddiction agencies and the poor 
lewis 50 a prominent wall street veteran had faced up to 15 
years in prison and a 750000 fine his firm sb lewis amp co 
was fined 400000 for violating federal securities laws 
the stock manipulation raised the value of firemans fund stock 
immediately before a longtime lewis client american express co 
sold a large amount of shares in a new public offering 
american express which invested 4 million to help lewis start 
his brokerage in 1980 was never charged and there is no proof 
that it or lewis profited from the manipulation but under federal 
securities laws profit isnt necessary to commit a crime 
lewis maintained he was not motivated by greed but by a desire 
to punish rival speculators attempting to bid down the price of 
firemans fund in anticipation of the new stock offering the 
government disagreed 
lewis attempts to portray himself as a misguided watchdog of 
the markets are simply not supported by the facts which show 
instead a straightforward market manipulation designed to assist a 
close business associate american express prosecutors said in 
court papers 
columbia university securities law professor john c coffee jr 
said lewis contention that no one was harmed in the manipulation 
was misplaced 
people were buying these securities as a price that was 
inflated and artificial he said 
prosecutors alleged that at lewis request jefferies bought 
more than 400000 shares of firemans fund on may 8 1986 
successfully driving its price up 12 cents to 38 a share 
a day later american express announced it would sell 8 million 
shares of its 41 percentowned firemans fund at 4150 a share a 
new stock offering that had been widely expected 
prosecutors said american express made 88 million from the sale 
but they never offered evidence that any of that profit was tainted 
by what lewis did 
