<DOCNO> AP891219-0203 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the electric cords that dangle from the 
fronts of cars on the northern plains are an oddity to strangers 
but a lifeline to residents 
the cords run to engine heaters that help cars start on brutally 
cold mornings folks on the plains have been known to call the 
devices inventor andrew freeman a saint 
i had a guy come up to me in a store the other day and thank 
me for inventing the heater the 80yearold freeman said monday 
he said he never would have gotten his car started that day 
without it i get a kick out of things like that 
strangers to the region point to the heater cords showing 
through the grillwork and ask whether they belong to electric cars 
but mark ewens a national weather service forecaster in fargo 
said the heaters have become necessary equipment in north dakota 
and other midwestern states 
we all have them we all use them ewens said when the 
air temperature is 33 degrees below zero when you get off work at 7 
am theres no way youd get the car started if you didnt have 
it plugged in 
freeman a north dakota native who lives in grand forks created 
his first heater out of necessity he got a patent on the device in 
1947 
tired of being unable to start his car in the winter he devised 
a heater that consisted of a brass cylinder about the size of a 
finger it contained a heating element attached to the end of a 
bolt 
the bolt replaced one of the headbolts in the engine and the 
cylinder with the heating element extended into the engine water 
jacket a cord attached to the top of the bolt plugged into an 
electrical outlet 
as cars changed freeman invented two other heaters a frost 
plug heater that attached to the side of the engine and an external 
tank heater 
drivers who want to make certain their cars start simply can go 
to a service station and have an engine heater installed for 
roughly 50 its cord is plugged into an outlet at night and the 
car is warm and ready to go in the morning 
freemans invention should get plenty of use in the coming days 
the temperature is not expected to climb above zero for the rest of 
the week 
ewens said decembers cold weather is not that unusual 
i think people have really poor meterological memories he 
said monday weve just had a few years of really mild winters 
now were back to normal 
and despite the cold freeman gets a warm twinge of pride when 
he sees all those cars with heater cords 
you walk around town and you see a lot of cars with plugs 
hanging out of them and you realize youre the guy who got that 
started 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

