<TEXT>
housing starts fell 47 percent in november 
after rising 13 percent a month earlier the government reported 
today 
the commerce department said new homes and apartments were built 
at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 136 million units last 
month down from a revised 143 million units in october 
the october increase was the largest since december 1986 starts 
had fallen 49 percent in september 
the report was fresh evidence of the sluggishness in the housing 
industry construction has been one of the economic sectors slowed 
by high interest rates resulting from the federal reserves grip on 
credit as it strives to curtail inflation 
in addition to its effect on construction jobs and the building 
materials industries the housing industry has an impact on other 
related industries such as home appliances and furnishings 
interest rates ranged from 982 percent to 974 percent in 
november according to surveys by the federal home loan mortgage 
corp total housing starts during the first 11 months of the year 
were down 65 percent from the same period of 1988 
construction of singlefamily homes in november dropped 09 
percent to an annual rate of 102 million units singlefamily 
starts had risen 55 percent in october 
apartment construction fell 144 percent in november to an 
annual rate of 346000 units after jumping 379 percent in october 
it had fallen 136 percent in september 
the south had the steepest decline down 113 percent to 495000 
units after rising 148 percent in october starts in the west also 
fell down 53 percent to 375000 units 
starts increased 37 percent to 305000 units in the midwest and 
33 percent to 295000 units in the northeast 
applications for building permits a barometer of future housing 
activity edged down 17 percent after rising 28 percent in 
october 
