<DOCNO> AP891219-0214 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the nations car market is so suffused with 
lookalike brands and models that competition increasingly will be 
forced into pricing says a professor who has studied the market 
for three decades 
he forecasts competitive pricing over the next few years like 
weve never seen before with potentially severe damage to 
products lines and even to entire manufacturing operations 
therell be a shakeout says professor eugene jennings of 
michigan state university an adviser to top corporate executives 
and an observer of the automotive industry whose opinions are 
widely sought 
we go into the 1990s with homogenization of design and style 
clear across the board said jennings who earlier attributed 
some of general motors lost market share to a lack of 
distinctiveness among its own brands 
now he says sameness pervades the whole industry to such an 
extent that product differences are even too subtle for 
advertising being observable only after salesmen call attention to 
them in the showroom 
but getting buyers into the showrooms particularly for cars 
with little curb appeal is more difficult than ever jennings 
says especially after two years in which sales were kept strong by 
drawing from future markets 
he says it is unlikely that any one manufacturer intended it 
this way but that they reacted in similar conservative ways to a 
fear of overcapacity in the industry rather than risk losing share 
through unacceptable innovations 
the consequences were too great if they guessed wrong said 
jennings in an interview new concepts would have presented too 
much risk and yet he suggested it might take the assumption of 
such risk to make a breakthrough 
the rare market situation already is reflected in advertising 
where he says more and more money is spent simply to break 
through the clutter and confusion and images and themes 
substitute for product distinctiveness 
its almost as if automobiles have become a commodity said 
jennings a business professor and author of many books about the 
inner workings of corporations 
the pricing problem could hardly be more serious he says 
observing that prices are following the same conservative trend 
a bit above or below the category average and be prepared to 
make a deal 
while the sameness syndrome exists he says it will be 
difficult for many car lines to sustain premium prices since 
customers can easily switch to the same car made by a different 
manufacturer 
planning and development also are affected by the syndrome big 
spending in this area always has been risky if necessary since a 
new concept or radical style change might not be accepted 
the failure of fords edsel is a monument to that risk and more 
recently says jennings photographs of general motors saturn car 
a costly effort to rethink the entire production process were 
greeted by yawns 
in the current market where sales already have been 
borrowed from model years to come and with large overcapacity 
in manufacturing operations the risk is magnified no one can 
afford to have an edsel says jennings 
while assumption of that risk might eventually be the only way 
to dissolve the stalemate jennings feels for the time being 
companies most likely will fight their battle on the pricing front 
prices will not hold at premium levels he states 
