<TEXT>
it wasnt quite lindbergh but a texas university 
professor earned his footnote in aviation history tuesday when he 
completed the first transatlantic flight in an ethanolfueled 
airplane 
max shauck a mathematics instructor at baylor university in 
waco texas landed at the small toussuslenoble airport southwest 
of paris after a onehour flight from tours 
he set out with italian copilot grazia zanin from waco on sept 
15 in a light experimental aircraft that carried them through often 
rough weather to canada the azores portugal spain and finally 
france 
we feel we have proved that ethanol is a very reliable fuel 
shauck said you cant get across the atlantic on an unreliable 
fuel 
proving the merits of the relatively cheap nonpolluting 
ethanol compared to standard fuel drove shauck make the journey 
which he funded himself at more cost than i care to think about 
ethanol is essentially an alcohol fuel made from vegetable 
matter usually corn in the united states and sugar beets in 
europe shauck who also does air pollution research at baylor 
says ethanol retails for about 120 per gallon in the united 
states compared to 180 for highoctane aviation fuel 
it produces more power it burns cooler and theres a lot less 
pollution he said but we had to go out of our way sometimes 
to find it 
indeed shauck and zanins flight log includes a hodgepodge of 
small stopovers in north america chosen chiefly because ethanol 
could be delivered there 
these included paducah ky newark ohio hazelton pa and 
suffolk ny the plane also stopped at shaucks hometown of 
mansfield ohio 
in canada they stopped at moncton and st pierreetmiquelon 
before lifting off from st johns newfoundland on oct 20 for 
flores in the azore islands a 2000mile crossing made terrifying 
by rain and thunderstorms 
its a long way over a lot of water when youre flying a 
little plane looking for little islands he said we didnt 
have sophisticated navigation equipment 
they waited in the azores for nearly three weeks for a shipment 
of ethanol to arrive before flying to lisbon nov 10 shauck 54 
and ms zanin 33 made stops in bilbao spain and bordeaux 
rochetsuryon and tours in france 
technically they became the first people to cross the atlantic 
in an ethanolfueled plane the minute they touched down in 
portugal but the original plan they filed with american 
authorities was from suffolk county ny airport to paris 
the fiberglass aircraft a sort of flying wing built by the 
velocity corp of sebastian fla featured elevators normally 
found on the tail at the front of the airplane and a propellor 
mounted on the back 
the whole contraption weighs about 2100 pounds and can reach a 
top speed of 200 mph 
shauck resists comparison with american aviator charles 
lindbergh first man to cross the atlantic in a flight from new 
york to le bourget airport in paris on may 31 1927 
he is a hero shauck said everything now is different 
than it was in his day i avoided going to le bourget because i 
didnt want to be compared to him 
shauck said he would take a commercial flight back to texas but 
that the aircraft will make one more trip to ms zanins 
hometown trieste 
</TEXT>
